values.Risk Identified:
1.1 D y s f u n c t i o n a l
communication channels.
values.Mitigation Measures/ Action Points:
Testing telephone lines, net connectivity
and additional dedicated lines. Frequent
dry run to be conducted.

values.Risk Identified:
1.2 Ineffective communication
of SLA with the Data Entry
Operators with EROs/
DEOs.
values.Mitigation Measures/ Action Points:
Regular monitoring of the work of District
Programmers and Data Entry Operators to
be mandated in the SLA agreement.

values.Risk Identified:
2.1 Lack of training, capacity
to take peak load, incorrect
data entry.
values.Mitigation Measures/ Action Points:
Sensitization, awareness, repeated training.
Adhering to SOPs of ECI. Second level
checks for final data entry.

values.Work area:
3. EVM and
VVPAT Security
and Management
values.Risk Identified:
3.1 Hazards of collecting
and transporting EVMs
from numerous source
stations.
values.Mitigation Measures/ Action Points:
EVMs from small warehouses can be
pooled at a few central places by the host
state for safer and more convenient picking
up by the borrowing state.

values.Risk Identified:
3.2 Damages to EVMs in
long transport.
values.Mitigation Measures/ Action Points: Protocols to be followed to avoid damages.

values.Risk Identified:
3.3 Inadequate and unsafe
storage of EVMs.
values.Mitigation Measures/ Action Points:
Dedicated warehouses to be built, with
required security features such as strong,
robust doors, CCTV camera, etc.

values.Risk Identified:
3.4 Unused expirable items
like VVPAT printing paper,
power- pack, etc.
values.Mitigation Measures/ Action Points:
Centralized stock-keeping to track the
unused consumables and transfer to the
poll-going states. Following ECIâ€™s new
norms for disposal of Battery of EVM and
VVPAT as per guidelines.

3.6 Hastily assembled,
inadequate technical
manpower to supervise
EVMs.
values.Guidelines to be formulated for safe and:
BEL & ECIL to be mandated to deploy the
necessary numbers of adequately trained
personnel for EVM-testing and managing.

3.7 Checking compatibility of
VVPAT with EVM model.
values.Guidelines to be formulated for safe and:
In case of VVPATs being used, it is
essential to check whether EVM available
is compatible with VVPAT.

3.8 Quality of thermal paper
for VVPAT.
values.Guidelines to be formulated for safe and:
As thermal paper has a definite life, it is
crucial to ensure adequate supplies of
fresh thermal paper. Date of manufacturing
needs to be checked.

3.9 Scope of complaint in case
of hasty FLC in absence
of political parties /
candidates.
values.Guidelines to be formulated for safe and:
At every stage of EVM/VVPAT preparation
and randomization, it must be ensured
that representatives of major political
parties, candidates/agents are present;
their signature should be obtained for the
proceedings; subject to ECI instructions,
they should be asked to press buttons for
their satisfaction in respect of the correct
functioning of both EVMs and VVPATs,
and such events of participation by stake
holders must be video graphed. Monitoring
through webcasting during FLC.

3.10 Undeleted previous data
may cause avoidable
doubts.
values.Guidelines to be formulated for safe and:
Receiving districts must resolve with the
sending districts as to whether the previous
data/candidate- setting on EVM/ VVPAT
has been properly deleted. If not, the
deletion should be ensured at the time of
FLC, following ECI guidelines.

3.11 Non-functioning of GPS
tracking of machines.
values.Guidelines to be formulated for safe and:
To be included in training module of Sector
Officer. Dry run to be done on P-3 day.

Ensuring preservation of SLU in the
custody of DEO till P+1 day.

3.13 Improper loading o f
symbol in VVPAT.
values.Guidelines to be formulated for safe and:
Checking the printed ballot slips with 7A
by at least two teams meticulously.

3.14 Non-implementation
of correct machine
replacement protocol.
values.Guidelines to be formulated for safe and:
Emphasis in training on replacement
protocol at Mock poll and during poll.
Train the Sector Officer adequately

3.15 VVPAT not kept vertical
while in movement.
values.Guidelines to be formulated for safe and:
Train all concerned in easily rememberable
way. â€˜Like when to work we are to standâ€™
means before working keep the knob
vertical, else horizontal.

3.16 Replace machines due to
exhaustion of battery.
values.Guidelines to be formulated for safe and:
Train the Polling party on battery
replacement protocol and keep extra
battery available.

values.3.17 Improper storage o f\nABCD category:
3.18 Reserve machines are
exhausted due to poor
reserve management on
poll day.
values.Train the team about the different stora:
Keep sufficient reserve machines. Follow
new guidelines of pasting of stickers.
Keep extra machines for reintroduction for
extreme exigency.

values.3.17 Improper storage o f\nABCD category:
3.19 Polling Personnel
should not transport
EVMs/VVPATs in any
unauthorized vehicles, even
if there is any breakdown.
They should not stop
with vehicles in any
unauthorized place.
values.Train the team about the different stora:
Suitable instructions to polling personnel
should be given in this regard. Arrangement
for reserve vehicles should be kept at
different locations.

values.3.17 Improper storage o f\nABCD category:
4.1 Compromise on quality
and increase in costs on
account of decentralized
procurement of election
materials.
values.Train the team about the different stora:
For as many standard and common items
as feasible, centralized procurement
decisions should be taken to get quality
items at competitive rates.

Assessment to be made on the basis
of probable auxiliary booths, probable
damages and maintenance of adequate
reserves. Proper training for correct use.
No use of old expired materials.

Nos. of booth. Housing
of auxiliaries/ additional
polling stations. Polling
stations not on ground floor.

and making detailed planning. Polling
stations to be on ground floor.

Fund.

values.If the location is very remote or diffic:
Analysis of vulnerability of polling stations
should be done well in advance, along with
the mapping of vulnerable areas.

values.6.4 Remoteness of polling\nstations or n:
6.6 Housing polling stations
in private buildings with
possibility of allegations.
values.If the location is very remote or diffic:
While grant-in-aid private institutions can
be considered, unaided private institutions
should be used only after due diligence
about the institutionâ€™s affiliations, and after
exhausting all possible government or
semi-government structures.

values.6.4 Remoteness of polling\nstations or n:
6.7 Lack of minimum facilities
at Polling Stations.
values.If the location is very remote or diffic:
Polling Stations with deficient facilities
should be marked and notified to the
concerned government department for
completing in time. Such building must be
subjected to one more physical verification
before it is proposed as a polling station.
Photographs of such buildings, before and
after repairs, should be maintained. Latest
AMF guidelines of the Commission to be
followed.

All possible means need to be deployed
to ensure that every polling station is in
some way connected. In case of severely
remote locations, alternative ways such as
deploying HAM Radio operators, Satellite
phones, and police wireless coverage, etc.
to be explored.

values.6.4 Remoteness of polling\nstations or n:
6.9 Appropriate awareness
of any new booth
created/ auxiliary voting
arrangement.
values.If the location is very remote or diffic:
Proper awareness to be made to electors
/candidates/political parties about the
voting arrangement in newly created booth
and auxiliary booth

values.6.4 Remoteness of polling\nstations or n:
6.10 Conversion of P-3 Polling
Stations into P-2.
values.If the location is very remote or diffic:
DEO to explore alternative Polling station
to minimize P-3 into P-2 PSs.

values.6.4 Remoteness of polling\nstations or n:
6.11 For hassle free polling
experience, all Polling
Stations shall be on ground
floor / entry level.
values.If the location is very remote or diffic:
Such Polling stations shall be explored
before election for voters especially PwDs
/ Senior citizens.

values.6.4 Remoteness of polling\nstations or n:
7.1 â€˜Law and orderâ€™ based
inputs may not be sufficient
to secure a clean poll.
values.If the location is very remote or diffic:
Analyze poll-related past incidents and
emphasize on intelligent examination of
voting statistics, electoral registration,
public grievance, present-day rivalry, etc.
along with â€˜law and orderâ€™ inputs.

values.6.4 Remoteness of polling\nstations or n:
7.2 Incomplete analysis to
decide the degree of
sensitivity may lead to gaps
in election management for
a clean poll.
values.If the location is very remote or diffic:
Inputs must be obtained from various
sources to decide on vulnerability
mapping. Worry list to be collected from
all candidates.

values.7.3 Delayed proceedings in\npreventive c:
7.4 Unrealistic demand for
CAPF conveys dependence
on central forces for
ensuring orderly polls.
values.About six months before the probable\nan:
Assessment of extra forces should be based
on situation analysis after completing
vulnerability mapping. State level
sensitivities such as border areas, political
significance of constituencies, should act
as moderating points.

values.7.3 Delayed proceedings in\npreventive c:
7.5 A Deployment plan
prepared in an ad hoc
manner without taking
into consideration ground
realities on the basis of last

values.Maintenance of a risk profile incorporat:
Efficient use of transport including by
train and effective route planning ensures
that last minute challenges and risks are
mitigated. It is necessary not only to plan
but also have fallback measures. Skilled
drivers with good quality vehicles shall be
put on duty especially in hilly terrain for
safety.

Advance identification of accommodation
for incoming forces for their comfortable
stay as per prevailing weather conditions.
Good quality food shall be served on time.
A Nodal officer shall be appointed for
overall coordination.

plan in an ad hoc manner
without taking into
consideration ground
realities and emphasis
on CAPF may result in
underutilization of stateâ€™s
resources such as Home
Guards, NCC and Civil

values.Maintenance of a risk profile incorporat:
Non-sensitive polling stations may be
supervised by home guards and civil
defense personnel, with due permission of
the authorities, NCC cadets can be utilized
for maintaining queues and providing
booth- level assistance to the females,
senior citizens and physically challenged
electors.

force measures such as
videography, web- casting
may result in spreading the
security forces too wide
for effective supervision of
sensitive locations.
values.Maintenance of a risk profile incorporat:
Videography of voters in queue and people
gathered outside, real- time webcasting
of poll in process, micro-observers
supervising the voting procedures, all such
non- force measures allow the security
forces time and resources to concentrate on
difficult and sensitive areas.

7.15 Constituency-wise and
District-wide deployment
may get influenced by
political factors.
values.Maintenance of a risk profile incorporat:
The actual allocation of the CAPF
companies district-wise and/or
constituency- wise should be done by the
DEOs in consultation with SPs and general
Observers.

basis of seniority for poll- deployment.

personnel should not be placed under

identified during poll- training, rather than
exposing the suffering employee to further
hazards and weakening the poll-duty teams

women with medical conditions should
be exempted. Employees with disability
should be posted to encourage differently-
abled voters, but should not be sent to very
inconvenient locations.

values.DEOs of districts having international\n:
All safety protocols must be followed.
Instructions should accompany E-Postal
Ballot on how to fill and how to send, so
as to avoid high rate of rejection of such
ballot papers.

Timely updating to be done of addresses in
respect of Service Voters. Repeated entries
should be deleted following due procedure.

values.27.1 Check-posts get\nabandoned on the e:
27.2 Election machineryâ€™s
focus being on Polling
Stations, the vulnerable
areas do not get adequate
protection during the day
and night prior to poll.
values.As far as feasible, some CAPF units\nsho:
A basic minimum enforcement of
vulnerable areas, border points and crucial
check-posts should be continued, as the
last 24 hours are the most vital for the
purpose of minimizing illegal influences
on electors.

values.27.1 Check-posts get\nabandoned on the e:
27.3 Last night contacts by
party functionaries allows
scope for extraneous
influences.
values.As far as feasible, some CAPF units\nsho:
All contesting candidates and their agents
should be video- trailed in their last day
of campaign. Prohibitory orders may be
imposed by Magistrates in areas where
possibility of mob violence or threatening
the weaker sections exists.

values.27.1 Check-posts get\nabandoned on the e:
27.4 Unattended serious
complains may raise
doubts over integrity of
poll-process.
values.As far as feasible, some CAPF units\nsho:
If serious allegations have been made about
personnel, machines, or violations of code
of conduct, all such grave matters must be
examined, resolved, and communicated to
the complainant as well as general public
so as to maintain trust in the systemâ€™s
efficiency and integrity.

values.27.1 Check-posts get\nabandoned on the e:
27.5 Inadequate protection of
EVMs and poll-material
in case PrO does not stay
overnight.
values.As far as feasible, some CAPF units\nsho:
Stay of PO and other essential staff should
be ensured on the night before poll-day.

values.27.1 Check-posts get\nabandoned on the e:
27.6 Non-functioning electrical
connection, water supply,
etc. at polling stations.
values.As far as feasible, some CAPF units\nsho:
Assured Minimum Facilities of Polling
Stations, along with connectivity status
must be cross-checked a week before the
poll day, so that corrective action can be
taken well in time. Latest AMF guideline
to be ensured and followed.

values.27.1 Check-posts get\nabandoned on the e:
27.7 Non-deletion of mock-
poll votes may result in
all votes becoming invalid
and vitiate the atmosphere.
values.As far as feasible, some CAPF units\nsho:
Along with mock poll conduct report,
mock poll data deletion report must be
collected from every polling station.
Communication channel to be kept clear to
avoid miscommunication.

values.27.1 Check-posts get\nabandoned on the e:
27.8 Agents of less powerful
candidates may either be
absent or discouraged
from continuing.
values.As far as feasible, some CAPF units\nsho:
Presence of only one agent should be taken
as a sign of imbalance of political power.
Very careful videography should be done
at such polling stations. ASD lists should
be scrutinized meticulously for possible
duplicate voters/impersonators. Hourly
voting figures should be assessed more
carefully at such stations.

values.27.9 Malfunctioning of EVMs /\nVVPATs du:
27.10 Overwhelming numbers
in late hours of poll may
disrupt poll process
through booth- jamming.
values.Spare EVMs / VVPATs to be kept\nwith mob:
Hourly reports to be assessed. In Polling
Stations with abnormally low voting figures
in the first half, special attention should be
given. If the number of electors waiting at
the end of poll is large (over one hundred),
additional officials and security should be
rushed to control the situation.

Last hours of polls should be monitored
continuously. POs should be trained to
report an incident of violence immediately.

Abnormally high polling in last one hour
must be investigated. Mock-poll data,
presence or absence of polling agents,
hourly poll figures, PO diary, etc. must be
properly examined. Any complaint about
rigging should be urgently looked into and
the EVM should be kept aside in strong
room.

values.27.9 Malfunctioning of EVMs /\nVVPATs du:
27.13 Casual challenge of test
vote to be discouraged
values.Spare EVMs / VVPATs to be kept\nwith mob:
PRO to follow detailed guideline under
49MA.

values.27.9 Malfunctioning of EVMs /\nVVPATs du:
27.14 Voter identification-
Mismatch between English
/ Vernacular versions of
electoral roll (Alphabetical
roll).
values.Spare EVMs / VVPATs to be kept\nwith mob:
Adequate training on acquaintance of
structure of Roll and its entries is to be
given to polling parties.

values.27.9 Malfunctioning of EVMs /\nVVPATs du:
27.15 Found machines in
unauthorized place/
vehicle.
values.Spare EVMs / VVPATs to be kept\nwith mob:
The machines should not be carried
in vehicle other than assigned vehicle.
Machines should not be kept in place other
than designated location. Precautionary
training required. Machines to be moved
through GPS tracked vehicle.

values.27.9 Malfunctioning of EVMs /\nVVPATs du:
28.1 Failing to notify the details
of counting time and place
as per Conduct of Election
Rules 1961.
values.Spare EVMs / VVPATs to be kept\nwith mob:
As law prescribes minimum one week
before the date, or the first of the dates,
fixed for the poll the notice by the RO,
mandatory monitoring on the dashboard is
needed.

values.27.9 Malfunctioning of EVMs /\nVVPATs du:
28.2 Failure in timely
submission of proposal of
counting hall for the ECI
in the prescribed format.
values.Spare EVMs / VVPATs to be kept\nwith mob:
At least 15 days before the poll, the proposal
must reach to the ECI.

values.27.9 Malfunctioning of EVMs /\nVVPATs du:
28.3 No inspection of the
counting hall.
values.Spare EVMs / VVPATs to be kept\nwith mob:
Mandatory inspection by the RO, much
before the due dates.

values.27.9 Malfunctioning of EVMs /\nVVPATs du:
29.1 Failure to have joint
inspection by the DM and
the SP.
values.Spare EVMs / VVPATs to be kept\nwith mob:
At least 21 days before the counting,
the inspection must be carried out from
security perspective.

values.Daily report on the dashboard to be\ngen:
Strong rooms should have adequate space
for EVMs along with VVPATs.

values.30.1 Failure in joint inspection\nas per:
31.1 Limited focus on Counting
Personnel requirements.
values.Daily report on the dashboard to be\ngen:
Adequate preparation for the database and
updation.

values.30.1 Failure in joint inspection\nas per:
31.2 Limited availability
of Micro Counting
Observers.
values.Daily report on the dashboard to be\ngen:
Advance preparation to be made to
identify and train Micro Observers as per
ECI guidelines.

Scheduled training with focus on hands on
session well in advance.

values.30.1 Failure in joint inspection\nas per:
32.1 Lack of awareness
amongst the candidates,
and other stakeholders
about entry restrictions.
values.Daily report on the dashboard to be\ngen:
Written as well as one-to-one
communication by the DEO/RO.

values.30.1 Failure in joint inspection\nas per:
32.2 Lack of Communication
with security agencies on
entry restrictions.
values.Daily report on the dashboard to be\ngen:
Advance meeting with the SP. Proper
briefing of those officers who will actually
manage entry/ exit points.

values.30.1 Failure in joint inspection\nas per:
32.3 No attention to detail
on seating arrangement,
electricity, connectivity.
values.Daily report on the dashboard to be\ngen:
Alternative arrangement to deal with
power failure is a must. Computer-systems
must always be protected from power
failure.

Adequate arrangement for dissemination.
Prior consultation with the State
Directorate of Information and publicity
should be done so as to avoid last-moment
rush for media passes.
RO and Observer must keep a close watch.

All rejected PB must be checked by the RO.
Where the margin of victory is less than
the number of postal ballot papers rejected
as invalid at the time of counting, all the
rejected PBs papers shall be mandatorily
re-verified by the RO before declaration of
result.

Arrangements should be made, as per
guidelines to complete postal ballot
counting in consonance with the EVM
counting. If there is in ordinate delay in
postal ballot counting and it continues
even after the EVM counting is completed,
it can cast aspersions.

values.30.1 Failure in joint inspection\nas per:
35.1 Precaution to be taken in
close contest.
values.Daily report on the dashboard to be\ngen:
RO and observer must take all precautions,
as listed by the ECI, before announcing
such results. Round wise tallying and
announcement must be done.

values.Along with videography of the entire\npr:
Before making it to public it must be
checked at meticulously by senior officials.

values.35.2. rivolous complaints to stop\ncount:
36.1 Hurried sealing may
cause loss of machines /
documents.
values.Along with videography of the entire\npr:
After the results are declared, EVMs, and
paper vote slips from out of VVPATs,
along with all statutory covers should be
sealed as per the prescribed process in a
careful manner. Strong room should be
sealed in presence of candidates/agents, in
supervision of a senior responsible officer.
The A+B category machines must be stored
separately AC wise after counting. It must
not be stored in Educational institution.

values.35.2. rivolous complaints to stop\ncount:
36.2 Aspersion on storage of
polled machines.
values.Along with videography of the entire\npr:
Daily inspection by DEO and RO of
strong room is at HQ, 3-4 times by DEO
and daily by RO if strong room is outside
headquartered.

values.35.2. rivolous complaints to stop\ncount:
37.2 The nuances of Election
petitions and guidelines
for example storage of
EVMâ€™s without AC/AS
segregation.
values.Along with videography of the entire\npr:
The election officials in the district as well
as Sub Divisional Election Offices should
be adequately trained with respect to
dealing with Election Petitions.

values.35.2. rivolous complaints to stop\ncount:
38.1 Delay in sending
expenditure report in ECI
format.
values.Along with videography of the entire\npr:
DEO must ensure that as per ECI guidelines,
all expenditure returns are sent to ECI well
in time.

values.35.2. rivolous complaints to stop\ncount:
38.2 Unexplained and
unresolved discrepancies
in expenditure figures.
values.Along with videography of the entire\npr:
Wherever differences Expenditure there in
figures are the as submitted by the candidates
and as given by the Expenditure Observers,
the figures need to be explained by the RO/
DEO, before being sent to the CEO/ECI. It
may be advisable to prescribe a time frame
in which the DEO must finish this job, and
till then they should not be allowed to leave
the district Reconciliation meeting shall be
organized timely after polling.

values.35.2. rivolous complaints to stop\ncount:
38.3 Notices not served on time
may cause delay in decision-
making.
values.Along with videography of the entire\npr:
DEOs need to ensure that all such notices
issued by ECI are delivered to candidates,
with acknowledgement, and timely replies
are taken from the candidates, on which
DEOs must provide their clear opinion
before submitting to the ECI. Original
acknowledgement shall be sent to ECI.
